>actually on the higher end of animal size
Uh, "sort of." There are a lot of species that are our size and larger.

Consider if you measure by mass or by height/length. The biggest cats (lions, tigers, jaguars) can hit 8 feet ro more from nose to butt (tail not included). That's BEFORE they stand up on the hind legs in an anthro pose ... then you can add 1 foot easily, if not 2 feet.

A wolf (your example) can easily be six feet nose-to-butt. Stand on their hind feet and seven feet becomes a very reasonable height. Even a coyote can be over 5 feet long. Stand up and they can be 6 feet or so.

Obviously there are then zebra/horses, cows, elk, deer, buffalo.

Humans by mass don't hit the top 10%. By height, I'm not sure they do either. In the top 20% for height, easily ... so from that standard we're on the "higher end." Interesting question if we make the top 20% by mass, but it seems top 25% might be a safe guess.

Average human height is about 5 and a half feet, lots of humans are shorter and 6 feet is only common in certain locals. Same for weight. 150 pounds probably isn't too far off for total average of humanity, even though "certain countries" produce lardbeasts in the 300 pound and up range to skew statistics.

I hunt, to give an example. Just this last season I took two white tail doe (a fairly smallish species of deer), one was 160 pounds the other was 180. On hind legs, they would easily stand 7 feet or more. A mule deer is a solid 20% larger, and elk are larger than horses. Horses are huge as all fuck, they can weigh a full ton (2000 pounds).
